  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Legislation to combat money laundering has evolved significantly over the past few decades:\n\n1. Key Milestones:\n- 1970: Bank Secrecy Act (first major US anti-money laundering legislation)\n- 1989: Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established\n- 2001: USA PATRIOT Act expanded anti-money laundering regulations\n\n2. Major Legislative Developments:\n- Increased reporting requirements for financial institutions\n- Enhanced customer due diligence procedures\n- Stricter Know Your Customer (KYC) regulations\n- Expanded definition of money laundering offenses\n- International cooperation and information sharing\n\n3. Global Regulatory Trends:\n- Comprehensive risk-based approaches\n- Digital currency and cryptocurrency regulations\n- Increased penalties for non-compliance\n- More sophisticated monitoring technologies\n- Emphasis on beneficial ownership transparency\n\n4. Compliance Requirements:\n- Mandatory suspicious transaction reporting\n- Regular internal audits\n- Employee training programs\n- Advanced transaction monitoring systems\n- Cross-border collaboration\n\n5. Recent Focus Areas:\n- Cryptocurrency regulation\n- Combating terrorist financing\n- Addressing emerging financial technologies\n- Enhanced international legal frameworks\n\nThese developments reflect ongoing efforts to address increasingly complex financial crime methods.",
